docs.name: Combine.Char
docs.comment:
This module contains `Char`-specific Parsers.

Avoid using this module if performance is a concern. You can achieve
everything that you can do with this module by using `Combine.regex`,
`Combine.string` or `Combine.primitive` and, in general, those will be
much faster.

# Parsers
@docs satisfy, char, anyChar, oneOf, noneOf, space, tab, newline, crlf, eol, lower, upper, digit, octDigit, hexDigit

values.name: anyChar
values.comment:
Parse any character.

    parse anyChar "a" ==
    -- Ok 'a'

    parse anyChar "" ==
    -- Err ["expected any character"]

values.name: char
values.comment:
Parse an exact character match.

    parse (char 'a') "a" ==
    -- Ok 'a'

    parse (char 'a') "b" ==
    -- Err ["expected 'a'"]

values.name: crlf
values.comment: Parse a `\r\n` sequence, returning a `\n` character.

values.name: digit
values.comment: Parse any base 10 digit.

values.name: eol
values.comment: Parse an end of line character or sequence, returning a `\n` character.

values.name: hexDigit
values.comment: Parse any base 16 digit.

values.name: lower
values.comment: Parse any lowercase character.

values.name: newline
values.comment: Parse a `\n` character.

values.name: noneOf
values.comment:
Parse a character that is not in the given list.

    parse (noneOf ['a', 'b']) "c" ==
    -- Ok 'c'

    parse (noneOf ['a', 'b']) "a" ==
    -- Err ["expected none of ['a','b']"]

values.name: octDigit
values.comment: Parse any base 8 digit.

values.name: oneOf
values.comment:
Parse a character from the given list.

    parse (oneOf ['a', 'b']) "a" ==
    -- Ok 'a'

    parse (oneOf ['a', 'b']) "c" ==
    -- Err ["expected one of ['a','b']"]

values.name: satisfy
values.comment:
Parse a character matching the predicate.

    parse (satisfy ((==) 'a')) "a" ==
    -- Ok 'a'

    parse (satisfy ((==) 'a')) "b" ==
    -- Err ["could not satisfy predicate"]

values.name: space
values.comment: Parse a space character.

values.name: tab
values.comment: Parse a `\t` character.

values.name: upper
values.comment: Parse any uppercase character.

docs.name: Combine
docs.comment:
This library provides facilities for parsing structured text data
into concrete Elm values.

## API Reference

* [Core Types](#core-types)
* [Running Parsers](#running-parsers)
* [Constructing Parsers](#constructing-parsers)
* [Parsers](#parsers)
* [Combinators](#combinators)
  * [Transforming Parsers](#transforming-parsers)
  * [Chaining Parsers](#chaining-parsers)
  * [Parser Combinators](#parser-combinators)
  * [State Combinators](#state-combinators)

## Core Types
@docs Parser, InputStream, ParseLocation, ParseContext, ParseResult, ParseErr, ParseOk

## Running Parsers
@docs parse, runParser

## Constructing Parsers
@docs primitive, app, lazy

## Parsers
@docs fail, succeed, string, regex, end, whitespace

## Combinators

### Transforming Parsers
@docs map, (<$>), (<$), ($>), mapError, (<?>)

### Chaining Parsers
@docs andThen, (>>=), andMap, (<*>), (<*), (*>), sequence

### Parser Combinators
@docs lookAhead, while, or, (<|>), choice, optional, maybe, many, many1, manyTill, sepBy, sepBy1, sepEndBy, sepEndBy1, skip, skipMany, skipMany1, chainl, chainr, count, between, parens, braces, brackets

### State Combinators
@docs withState, putState, modifyState, withLocation, withLine, withColumn, currentLocation, currentSourceLine, currentLine, currentColumn

aliases.name: InputStream
aliases.comment:
The input stream over which `Parser`s operate.

* `data` is the initial input provided by the user
* `input` is the remainder after running a parse
* `position` is the starting position of `input` in `data` after a parse
aliases.type: { data : String, input : String, position : Int }

aliases.name: ParseContext
aliases.comment:
A tuple representing the current parser state, the remaining input
stream and the parse result.  Don't worry about this type unless
you're writing your own `primitive` parsers.

aliases.name: ParseErr
aliases.comment:
A tuple representing a failed parse.  It contains the state after
running the parser, the remaining input stream and a list of
error messages.

aliases.name: ParseLocation
aliases.comment:
A record representing the current parse location in an InputStream.

* `source` the current line of source code
* `line` the current line number (starting at 1)
* `column` the current column (starting at 1)
aliases.type: { source : String, line : Int, column : Int }

aliases.name: ParseOk
aliases.comment:
A tuple representing a successful parse.  It contains the state
after running the parser, the remaining input stream and the
result.

aliases.name: ParseResult
aliases.comment:
Running a `Parser` results in one of two states:

* `Ok res` when the parser has successfully parsed the input
* `Err messages` when the parser has failed with a list of error messages.

types.name: Parser
types.comment:
The Parser type.

At their core, `Parser`s wrap functions from some `state` and an
`InputStream` to a tuple representing the new `state`, the
remaining `InputStream` and a `ParseResult res`.

values.comment:
Run a parser and return the value on the right on success.

    parse (string "true" $> True) "true"
    -- Ok True

    parse (string "true" $> True) "false"
    -- Err ["expected \"true\""]
values.type: Combine.Parser s x -> a -> Combine.Parser s a

values.comment:
Join two parsers, ignoring the result of the one on the left.

    unprefix : Parser s String
    unprefix =
      string ">"
        *> while ((==) ' ')
        *> while ((/=) ' ')

    parse unprefix "> a"
    -- Ok "a"
values.type: Combine.Parser s x -> Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s a

values.comment:
Run a parser and return the value on the left on success.

    parse (True <$ string "true") "true"
    -- Ok True

    parse (True <$ string "true") "false"
    -- Err ["expected \"true\""]
values.type: a -> Combine.Parser s x -> Combine.Parser s a

values.comment:
Infix version of `map`.

    parse (toString <$> int) "42"
    -- Ok "42"

    parse (toString <$> int) "abc"
    -- Err ["expected an integer"]
values.type: (a -> b) -> Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s b

values.comment:
Join two parsers, ignoring the result of the one on the right.

    unsuffix : Parser s String
    unsuffix =
      regex "[a-z]"
        <* regex "[!?]"

    parse unsuffix "a!"
    -- Ok "a"
values.type: Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s x -> Combine.Parser s a

values.comment:
Infix version of `andMap`.

    add : Int -> Int -> Int
    add = (+)

    plus : Parser s String
    plus = string "+"

    parse (add <$> int <*> (plus *> int)) "1+1"
    -- Ok 2
values.type: Combine.Parser s (a -> b) -> Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s b

values.comment:
Variant of `mapError` that replaces the Parser's error with a List
of a single string.

    parse (string "a" <?> "gimme an 'a'") "b"
    -- Err ["gimme an 'a'"]
values.type: Combine.Parser s a -> String -> Combine.Parser s a

values.comment: Synonym for `or`.
values.type: Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s a

values.comment:
Infix version of `andThen`.

    import Combine.Num exposing (int)

    choosy : Parser s String
    choosy =
      let
        createParser n =
          if n % 2 == 0 then
            string " is even"
          else
            string " is odd"
      in
        int >>= createParser

    parse choosy "1 is odd"
    -- Ok " is odd"

    parse choosy "2 is even"
    -- Ok " is even"

    parse choosy "1 is even"
    -- Err ["expected \" is odd\""]
values.type: Combine.Parser s a -> (a -> Combine.Parser s b) -> Combine.Parser s b

values.name: andMap
values.comment:
Sequence two parsers.

    import Combine.Num exposing (int)

    plus : Parser s String
    plus = string "+"

    sum : Parser s Int
    sum =
      int
        |> map (+)
        |> andMap (plus *> int)

    parse sum "1+2"
    -- Ok 3
values.type: Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s (a -> b) -> Combine.Parser s b

values.name: andThen
values.comment:
Sequence two parsers, passing the result of the first parser to a
function that returns the second parser. The value of the second
parser is returned on success.

    import Combine.Num exposing (int)

    choosy : Parser s String
    choosy =
      let
        createParser n =
          if n % 2 == 0 then
            string " is even"
          else
            string " is odd"
      in
        int
          |> andThen createParser

    parse choosy "1 is odd"
    -- Ok " is odd"

    parse choosy "2 is even"
    -- Ok " is even"

    parse choosy "1 is even"
    -- Err ["expected \" is odd\""]
values.type: (a -> Combine.Parser s b) -> Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s b

values.name: app
values.comment:
Unwrap a parser so it can be applied to a state and an input
stream.  This function is useful if you want to construct your own
parsers via `primitive`.  If you're using this outside of the context
of `primitive` then you might be doing something wrong so try asking
for help on the mailing list.

Here's how you would implement a greedy version of `manyTill` using
`primitive` and `app`:

    manyTill : Parser s a -> Parser s x -> Parser s (List a)
    manyTill p end =
      let
        accumulate acc state stream =
          case app end state stream of
            (rstate, rstream, Ok _) ->
              (rstate, rstream, Ok (List.reverse acc))

            _ ->
              case app p state stream of
                (rstate, rstream, Ok res) ->
                  accumulate (res :: acc) rstate rstream

                (estate, estream, Err ms) ->
                  (estate, estream, Err ms)
      in
        primitive <| accumulate []
values.type: Combine.Parser state res -> state -> Combine.InputStream -> Combine.ParseContext state res

values.name: between
values.comment:
Parse something between two other parsers.

The parser

    between (string "(") (string ")") (string "a")

is equivalent to the parser

    string "(" *> string "a" <* string ")"
values.type: Combine.Parser s l -> Combine.Parser s r -> Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s a

values.name: braces
values.comment: Parse something between braces `{}`.
values.type: Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s a

values.name: brackets
values.comment: Parse something between square brackets `[]`.
values.type: Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s a

values.name: chainl
values.comment:
Parse one or more occurences of `p` separated by `op`, recursively
apply all functions returned by `op` to the values returned by `p`. See
the `examples/Calc.elm` file for an example.
values.type: Combine.Parser s (a -> a -> a) -> Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s a

values.name: chainr
values.comment:
Similar to `chainl` but functions of `op` are applied in
right-associative order to the values of `p`.  See the
`examples/Python.elm` file for a usage example.
values.type: Combine.Parser s (a -> a -> a) -> Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s a

values.name: choice
values.comment:
Choose between a list of parsers.

    parse (choice [string "a", string "b"]) "a"
    -- Ok "a"

    parse (choice [string "a", string "b"]) "b"
    -- Ok "b"
values.type: List (Combine.Parser s a) -> Combine.Parser s a

values.name: count
values.comment: Parse `n` occurences of `p`.
values.type: Int -> Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s (List a)

values.name: currentColumn
values.comment: Get the current column in the input stream.

values.name: currentLine
values.comment: Get the current line in the input stream.

values.name: currentLocation
values.comment: Get the current `(line, column)` in the input stream.

values.name: currentSourceLine
values.comment: Get the current source line in the input stream.

values.name: end
values.comment:
Fail when the input is not empty.

    parse end ""
    -- Ok ()

    parse end "a"
    -- Err ["expected end of input"]

values.name: fail
values.comment:
Fail without consuming any input.

    parse (fail "some error") "hello"
    -- Err ["some error"]

values.name: lazy
values.comment:
Defer running a parser until it's actually required.  Use this
function to avoid "bad-recursion" errors.

    type Expression
      = ETerm String
      | EList (List E)

    name : Parser s String
    name = whitespace *> regex "[a-zA-Z]+" <* whitespace

    term : Parser s Expression
    term = ETerm <$> name

    list : Parser s Expression
    list =
      let
        -- helper is itself a function so we avoid the case where the
        -- value `list` tries to apply itself in its definition.
        helper () =
          EList <$> between (string "(") (string ")") (many (term <|> list))
      in
        -- lazy defers calling helper until it's actually needed.
        lazy helper

    parse list ""
    -- Err ["expected \"(\""]

    parse list "()"
    -- Ok (EList [])

    parse list "(a (b c))"
    -- Ok (EList [ETerm "a", EList [ETerm "b", ETerm "c"]])
values.type: (() -> Combine.Parser s a) -> Combine.Parser s a

values.name: lookAhead
values.comment: Apply a parser without consuming any input on success.
values.type: Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s a

values.name: many
values.comment:
Apply a parser zero or more times and return a list of the results.

    parse (many (string "a")) "aaab"
    -- Ok ["a", "a", "a"]

    parse (many (string "a")) "bbbb"
    -- Ok []

    parse (many (string "a")) ""
    -- Ok []
values.type: Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s (List a)

values.name: many1
values.comment:
Parse at least one result.

    parse (many1 (string "a")) "a"
    -- Ok ["a"]

    parse (many1 (string "a")) ""
    -- Err ["expected \"a\""]
values.type: Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s (List a)

values.name: manyTill
values.comment:
Apply parser `p` zero or more times until parser `end`
succeeds. On success, the list of `p`'s results is returned.

    string "<!--" *> manyTill anyChar (string "-->")
values.type: Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s end -> Combine.Parser s (List a)

values.name: map
values.comment:
Transform the result of a parser.

    let
      parser =
        string "a"
          |> map String.toUpper
    in
      parse parser "a"
      -- Ok "A"
values.type: (a -> b) -> Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s b

values.name: mapError
values.comment:
Transform the error of a parser.

    let
      parser =
        string "a"
          |> mapError (always ["bad input"])
    in
      parse parser b
      -- Err ["bad input"]
values.type: (List String -> List String) -> Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s a

values.name: maybe
values.comment:
Wrap the return value into a `Maybe`.  Returns `Nothing` on failure.

    parse (maybe (string "a")) "a"
    -- Ok (Just "a")

    parse (maybe (string "a")) "b"
    -- Ok Nothing
values.type: Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s (Maybe.Maybe a)

values.name: modifyState
values.comment: Modify the parser's state.

values.name: optional
values.comment:
Return a default value when the given parser fails.

    letterA : Parser s String
    letterA = optional "a" (string "a")

    parse letterA "a"
    -- Ok "a"

    parse letterA "b"
    -- Ok "a"
values.type: a -> Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s a

values.name: or
values.comment:
Choose between two parsers.

    parse (or (string "a") (string "b")) "a"
    -- Ok "a"

    parse (or (string "a") (string "b")) "b"
    -- Ok "b"

    parse (or (string "a") (string "b")) "c"
    -- Err ["expected \"a\"", "expected \"b\""]
values.type: Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s a

values.name: parens
values.comment: Parse something between parentheses.
values.type: Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s a

values.name: parse
values.comment:
Parse a string.  See `runParser` if your parser needs to manage
some internal state.

    import Combine.Num exposing (int)
    import String

    parseAnInteger : String -> Result String Int
    parseAnInteger input =
      case parse int input of
        Ok (_, stream, result) ->
          Ok result

        Err (_, stream, errors) ->
          Err (String.join " or " errors)

    parseAnInteger "123"
    -- Ok 123

    parseAnInteger "abc"
    -- Err "expected an integer"

values.name: primitive
values.comment:
Construct a new primitive Parser.

If you find yourself reaching for this function often consider opening
a [Github issue][issues] with the library to have your custom Parsers
included in the standard distribution.

[issues]: https://github.com/Bogdanp/elm-combine/issues
values.type: (state -> Combine.InputStream -> Combine.ParseContext state res) -> Combine.Parser state res

values.name: putState
values.comment: Replace the parser's state.

values.name: regex
values.comment:
Parse a Regex match.

Regular expressions must match from the beginning of the input and their
subgroups are ignored. A `^` is added implicitly to the beginning of
every pattern unless one already exists.

    parse (regex "a+") "aaaaab"
    -- Ok "aaaaa"

values.name: runParser
values.comment:
Parse a string while maintaining some internal state.

    import Combine.Num exposing (int)
    import String

    type alias Output =
      { count : Int
      , integers : List Int
      }

    statefulInt : Parse Int Int
    statefulInt =
      -- Parse an int, then increment the state and return the parsed
      -- int.  It's important that we try to parse the int _first_
      -- since modifying the state will always succeed.
      int <* modifyState ((+) 1)

    ints : Parse Int (List Int)
    ints =
      sepBy (string " ") statefulInt

    parseIntegers : String -> Result String Output
    parseIntegers input =
      case runParser ints 0 input of
        Ok (state, stream, ints) ->
          Ok { count = state, integers = ints }

        Err (state, stream, errors) ->
          Err (String.join " or " errors)

    parseIntegers ""
    -- Ok { count = 0, integers = [] }

    parseIntegers "1 2 3 45"
    -- Ok { count = 4, integers = [1, 2, 3, 45] }

    parseIntegers "1 a 2"
    -- Ok { count = 1, integers = [1] }
values.type: Combine.Parser state res -> state -> String -> Result.Result (Combine.ParseErr state) (Combine.ParseOk state res)

values.name: sepBy
values.comment:
Parser zero or more occurences of one parser separated by another.

    parse (sepBy (string ",") (string "a")) "b"
    -- Ok []

    parse (sepBy (string ",") (string "a")) "a,a,a"
    -- Ok ["a", "a", "a"]

    parse (sepBy (string ",") (string "a")) "a,a,b"
    -- Ok ["a", "a"]
values.type: Combine.Parser s x -> Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s (List a)

values.name: sepBy1
values.comment: Parse one or more occurences of one parser separated by another.
values.type: Combine.Parser s x -> Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s (List a)

values.name: sepEndBy
values.comment:
Parse zero or more occurences of one parser separated and
optionally ended by another.

    parse (sepEndBy (string ",") (string "a")) "a,a,a,"
    -- Ok ["a", "a", "a"]
values.type: Combine.Parser s x -> Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s (List a)

values.name: sepEndBy1
values.comment:
Parse one or more occurences of one parser separated and
optionally ended by another.

    parse (sepEndBy1 (string ",") (string "a")) ""
    -- Err ["expected \"a\""]

    parse (sepEndBy1 (string ",") (string "a")) "a"
    -- Ok ["a"]

    parse (sepEndBy1 (string ",") (string "a")) "a,"
    -- Ok ["a"]
values.type: Combine.Parser s x -> Combine.Parser s a -> Combine.Parser s (List a)

values.name: sequence
values.comment:
Run a list of parsers in sequence, accumulating the results.  The
main use case for this parser is when you want to combine a list of
parsers into a single, top-level, parser.  For most use cases, you'll
want to use one of the other combinators instead.

    parse (sequence [string "a", string "b"]) "ab"
    -- Ok ["a", "b"]

    parse (sequence [string "a", string "b"]) "ac"
    -- Err ["expected \"b\""]
values.type: List (Combine.Parser s a) -> Combine.Parser s (List a)

values.name: skip
values.comment: Apply a parser and skip its result.

values.name: skipMany
values.comment: Apply a parser and skip its result many times.

values.name: skipMany1
values.comment: Apply a parser and skip its result at least once.

values.name: string
values.comment:
Parse an exact string match.

    parse (string "hello") "hello world"
    -- Ok "hello"

    parse (string "hello") "goodbye"
    -- Err ["expected \"hello\""]

values.name: succeed
values.comment:
Return a value without consuming any input.

    parse (succeed 1) "a"
    -- Ok 1

values.name: while
values.comment:
Consume input while the predicate matches.

    parse (while ((/=) ' ')) "test 123"
    -- Ok "test"

values.name: whitespace
values.comment:
Parse zero or more whitespace characters.

    parse (whitespace *> string "hello") "hello"
    -- Ok "hello"

    parse (whitespace *> string "hello") "   hello"
    -- Ok "hello"

values.name: withColumn
values.comment: Get the current column and pipe it into a parser.
values.type: (Int -> Combine.Parser s a) -> Combine.Parser s a

values.name: withLine
values.comment: Get the current line and pipe it into a parser.
values.type: (Int -> Combine.Parser s a) -> Combine.Parser s a

values.name: withLocation
values.comment: Get the current position in the input stream and pipe it into a parser.
values.type: (Combine.ParseLocation -> Combine.Parser s a) -> Combine.Parser s a

values.name: withState
values.comment: Get the parser's state and pipe it into a parser.
values.type: (s -> Combine.Parser s a) -> Combine.Parser s a

aliases.name: Settings
aliases.comment: The type of date picker settings.
aliases.type: { placeholder : String , classNamespace : String , inputClassList : List ( String, Bool ) , inputName : Maybe.Maybe String , isDisabled : Date.Date -> Bool , dateFormatter : Date.Date -> String , dayFormatter : Date.Day -> String , monthFormatter : Date.Month -> String , yearFormatter : Int -> String , firstDayOfWeek : Date.Day , pickedDate : Maybe.Maybe Date.Date }

types.name: DatePicker
types.comment: The DatePicker model.

types.name: Msg
types.comment: An opaque type representing messages that are passed inside the DatePicker.

values.name: defaultSettings
init
values.comment:
Initialize a DatePicker given a Settings record.  You must execute
the returned command for the date picker to behave correctly.


    init =
      let
         (datePicker, datePickerFx) =
           DatePicker.init defaultSettings
      in
         { picker = datePicker } ! [ Cmd.map ToDatePicker datePickerfx ]

values.name: update
values.comment:
The date picker update function.  The third value in the returned
tuple represents the picked date, it is `Nothing` if no date was
picked or if the previously-picked date has not changed and `Just`
some date if it has.
values.type: DatePicker.Msg -> DatePicker.DatePicker -> ( DatePicker.DatePicker , Platform.Cmd.Cmd DatePicker.Msg , Maybe.Maybe Date.Date )

values.name: view
values.comment: The date picker view.

docs.name: QueryString
docs.comment:
This module exposes functions for working with query strings.

You can manipulate `QueryString`s:

    > empty
    |   |> add "a" "hello"
    |   |> add "a" "goodbye"
    |   |> add "b" "1"
    |   |> render
    "?a=hello&a=goodbye&b=1" : String

And you can parse and extract their parameters:

    > let
    |   qs = parse "?a=1&a=2&a=test&b=hello"
    |   a = qs |> many int "a"
    |   b = qs |> one string "b" |> Maybe.withDefault "goodbye"
    | in
    |   (a, b)
    ([1, 2], "hello")

## Types
@docs QueryString

## Constructing QueryStrings
@docs parse, empty

## Manipulating parameters
@docs render, add, remove, filter

## Extracting parameters
@docs all, one, many

### Parsers
@docs string, int

types.name: QueryString
types.comment: Represents a parsed query string.

values.name: add
values.comment:
Add a value to a key.

    > parse "?a=1&b=a&a=c"
    |   |> add "a" "2"
    |   |> render
    "?a=2&a=1&a=c&b=a" : String

    > parse "?a=1&b=a&a=c"
    |   |> add "d" "hello"
    |   |> render
    "?a=1&a=c&b=a&d=hello" : String

values.name: all
values.comment:
Retrieve all of the values for a given key.

    > parse "?a=1&a=2"
    |   |> all "a"
    ["1","2"] : List String

    > parse "?a=1&a=2"
    |   |> all "b"
    [] : List String

values.name: empty
values.comment: Construct an empty QueryString.

values.name: filter
values.comment:
Filter a key's values.

    > parse "?a=1&b=a&a=c"
    |   |> filter "a" ((==) "1")
    |   |> render
    "?a=1&b=a" : String

values.name: int
values.comment: A Parser that accepts any integer.

values.name: many
values.comment:
Retrieve zero or more values for some key. Values are funneled
through the given parser before being returned.

    > parse "?a=1&a=c&a=2"
    |   |> many int "a"
    [1,2] : List Int
values.type: Combine.Parser () a -> String -> QueryString.QueryString -> List a

values.name: one
values.comment:
Retrieve a single value for a given key. Values are funneled through
the given parser before being returned.

    > parse "?a=1&a=2"
    |   |> one string "a"
    Just "2" : Maybe.Maybe String

    > parse "?a=1&a=2"
    |   |> one int "a"
    Just 2 : Maybe.Maybe Int

    > parse "?a=1&a=c"
    |   |> one int "a"
    Just 1 : Maybe.Maybe Int
values.type: Combine.Parser () a -> String -> QueryString.QueryString -> Maybe.Maybe a

values.name: parse
values.comment:
Turn a String into a QueryString. The initial `?` is optional.

    > parse ""
    QueryString (Dict.fromList []) : QueryString

    > parse "?a=1&b=c&a=2"
    QueryString (Dict.fromList [("a",["1","2"]),("b",["c"])])
        : QueryString

    > parse "a=1&b=c&a=2"
    QueryString (Dict.fromList [("a",["1","2"]),("b",["c"])])
        : QueryString

values.name: remove
values.comment:
Remove a key.

    > parse "?a=1&b=a&a=c"
    |   |> remove "a"
    |   |> render
    "?b=a" : String

    > parse "?a=1&b=a&a=c"
    |   |> remove "c"
    |   |> render
    "?a=1&a=c&b=a" : String

values.name: render
values.comment:
Render a QueryString to a String.

    > render (parse "?a=1&b=a&a=c")
    "?a=1&a=c&b=a" : String

values.name: string
values.comment: A Parser that accepts any string.

docs.name: Route

types.name: Route
types.comment:
Routes represent concrete parsers for paths. Routes can be combined
and they keep track of their path components in order to provide
automatic reverse routing.

types.name: Router
types.comment:
A Router is, at its core, a List of Routes.

    sitemap : Router a
    sitemap = router [routeA, routeB]

values.comment:
A synonym for `route`.

    type Sitemap
      = HomeR

    homeR : Route Sitemap
    homeR = HomeR := static ""

A synonym for `and`.

    type Sitemap
      = AddR Int Int

    addR = AddR := int </> int
    sitemap = router [addR]

    > match sitemap "/1/2"
    Just (AddR 1 2) : Maybe Sitemap
values.type: Route.Route (a -> b) -> Route.Route (b -> c) -> Route.Route (a -> c)

values.name: and
values.comment:
Compose two Routes.

    type Sitemap
      = AddR Int Int

    addR = AddR := int `and` int
    sitemap = router [addR]

    > match sitemap "/1/2"
    Just (AddR 1 2) : Maybe Sitemap
values.type: Route.Route (a -> b) -> Route.Route (b -> c) -> Route.Route (a -> c)

values.name: custom
values.comment:
Create a Route with a custom Parser.

    import Combine exposing (..)
    import Combine.Infix exposing (..)

    type Category
      = Snippet
      | Post

    type Sitemap
      = CategoryR Category

    categoryR = CategoryR := static "categories" </> custom categoryParser
    sitemap = router [categoryR]

    > match sitemap "/categories/a"
    Nothing : Maybe Sitemap

    > match sitemap "/categories/Post"
    Just (CategoryR Post) : Maybe Sitemap

    > match sitemap "/categories/Snippet"
    Just (CategoryR Snippet) : Maybe Sitemap

See `examples/Custom.elm` for a complete example.

values.name: int
values.comment:
A Route that matches any integer.

    type Sitemap
      = UserR Int

    userR = UserR := static "users" </> int
    sitemap = router [userR]

    > match sitemap "/users/a"
    Nothing : Maybe Sitemap

    > match sitemap "/users/1"
    Just (UserR 1) : Maybe Sitemap

    > match sitemap "/users/-1"
    Just (UserR -1) : Maybe Sitemap

values.name: match
values.comment:
Given a Router and an arbitrary String representing a path, this
function will return the first Route that matches that path.

    type Sitemap
      = HomeR
      | UsersR
      | UserR Int

    homeR = HomeR := static ""
    usersR = UsersR := static "users"
    usersR = UserR := static "users" </> int
    sitemap = router [homeR, userR, usersR]

    > match sitemap "/a"
    Nothing : Maybe Sitemap

    > match sitemap "/"
    Just HomeR : Maybe Sitemap

    > match sitemap "/users"
    Just UsersR : Maybe Sitemap

    > match sitemap "/users/1"
    Just (UserR 1) : Maybe Sitemap

    > match sitemap "/users/1"
    Just (UserR 1) : Maybe Sitemap

values.name: reverse
values.comment:
Render a path given a Route and a list of route components.

    type Sitemap
      = HomeR
      | UsersR
      | UserR Int

    homeR = HomeR := static ""
    usersR = UsersR := static "users"
    usersR = UserR := static "users" </> int
    sitemap = router [homeR, userR, usersR]

    > reverse homeR []
    "/"

    > reverse usersR []
    "/users"

    > reverse userR ["1"]
    "/users/1"

If you are willing to write some boilerplate, `reverse` can be used to
construct a type safe reverse routing function specific to your
application:

    toString : Sitemap -> String
    toString r =
      case r of
        HomeR  -> reverse homeR []
        UsersR  -> reverse usersR []
        UserR uid -> reverse userR [toString uid]

    > toString HomeR
    "/"

    > toString UsersR
    "/users"

    > toString (UserR 1)
    "/users/1"

`reverse` will crash at runtime if there is a mismatch between the
route and the list of arguments that is passed in. For example:

    > reverse deepR []
    Error: Ran into a `Debug.crash` in module `Route`

    This was caused by the `case` expression between lines 145 and 175.
    One of the branches ended with a crash and the following value got through:

        ([],[CInt,CInt,CInt])

    The message provided by the code author is:

        'reverse' called with an unexpected number of arguments

    > reverse deepR ["a"]
    Error: Ran into a `Debug.crash` in module `Route`

    This was caused by the `case` expression between lines 171 and 176.
    One of the branches ended with a crash and the following value got through:

        Err ("could not convert string 'a' to an Int")

    The message provided by the code author is:

        could not convert string 'a' to an Int in a call to 'reverse'

values.name: route
values.comment:
Declare a Route.

    type Sitemap
      = HomeR

    homeR : Route Sitemap
    homeR = route HomeR (static "")

values.name: router
values.comment:
Construct a Router from a list of Routes.

    type Sitemap
      = HomeR
      | BlogR

    homeR = HomeR := static ""
    blogR = BlogR := static "blog"
    sitemap = router [homeR, blogR]

values.name: static
values.comment:
Create a Route that matches a static String.

    type Sitemap
      = BlogR

    blogR = BlogR := static "blog"
    sitemap = router [blogR]

    > match sitemap "/blog"
    Just BlogR : Maybe Sitemap

values.name: string
values.comment:
A Route that matches any string.

    type Sitemap
      = PostR String

    postR = PostR := static "posts" </> string
    sitemap = router [postR]

    > match sitemap "/posts/"
    Nothing : Maybe Sitemap

    > match sitemap "/posts/hello-world/test"
    Nothing : Maybe Sitemap

    > match sitemap "/posts/hello-world"
    Just (PostR "hello-world") : Maybe Sitemap

docs.name: Time.ZonedDateTime

types.name: ZonedDateTime
types.comment:
ZoneDateTime is the opaque type for all ZonedDateTime values.
Values of this type represent a `(TimeZone, DateTime)` pair.

values.name: abbreviation
values.comment: abbreviation returns a ZonedDateTime's abbreviation at that time.

values.name: day
values.comment: day returns a ZonedDateTime's day.

values.name: fromDateTime
values.comment:
fromDateTime constructs a ZonedDateTime value from a TimeZone and
a DateTime.

values.name: fromISO8601
values.comment:
fromISO8601 parses an ISO8601-formatted string into a
ZonedDateTime object, adjusting for its offset.

values.name: hour
values.comment: hour returns a ZonedDateTime's hour.

values.name: millisecond
values.comment: millisecond returns a ZonedDateTime's millisecond.

values.name: minute
values.comment: minute returns a ZonedDateTime's minute.

values.name: month
values.comment: month returns a ZonedDateTime's month.

values.name: second
values.comment: second returns a ZonedDateTime's second.

values.name: timeZone
values.comment: timeZone returns a ZonedDatetime's TimeZone.

values.name: toDateTime
values.comment: toDateTime converts a ZonedDateTime to a UTC DateTime value.

values.name: toISO8601
values.comment: toISO8601 renders a ZonedDateTime in ISO8601 format.

values.name: utcOffset
values.comment:
utcOffset returns a ZonedDateTime's offset from UTC in
milliseconds at that time.

values.name: utcOffsetString
values.comment:
utcOffsetString returns a ZonedDateTime's UTC offset at that time
as a string.

values.name: weekday
values.comment: weekday returns a ZonedDateTime's day of the week.

values.name: year
values.comment: year returns a ZonedDateTime's year.

values.name: zero
values.comment:
zero represents the first millisecond of the first day of the
current era.  Use it to build `ZonedDateTime` values:

    -- 0-01-01T00:00:00+02:00
    zonedDateTime (europe_bucharest ()) zero

    -- 2016-01-01T00:00:00+02:00
    zonedDateTime (europe_bucharest ()) { zero | year = 2016 }

    -- 2016-05-29T13:00:00+02:00
    zonedDateTime (europe_bucharest ()) { zero | year = 2016, month = 5, day = 29, hour = 13 }

values.name: zonedDateTime
values.comment:
zonedDateTime constructs a ZonedDateTime value given a TimeZone, a
date and a time.  Invalid values are clamped to the nearest valid date
and time.

DateTime is the opaque type for all DateTime values.  Values of this
type represent a valid Date and a time offset from midnight.

docs.name: Time.Date

aliases.name: DateDelta
aliases.comment: DateDelta represents a delta between two dates.
aliases.type: { years : Int, months : Int, days : Int }

types.name: Date
types.comment:
Date is the opaque type for all Date values.  Values of this type
are guaranteed to represent valid proleptic Gregorian calendar dates.

types.name: Weekday
types.comment: Data type used to represent the days of the week.

values.name: addDays
values.comment:
days adds an exact number (positive or negative) of days to a
Date.  Adding or subtracting days always produces a valid Date so
there is no fuzzing logic here like there is in `add{Months,Years}`.

values.name: addMonths
values.comment:
addMonths adds a relative number (positive or negative) of months to
a Date, ensuring that the return value represents a valid Date.  Its
semantics are the same as `addYears`.

values.name: addYears
values.comment:
addYears adds a relative number (positive or negative) of years to
a Date, ensuring that the return value represents a valid Date.  If
the new date is not valid, days are subtracted from it until a valid
Date can be produced.

values.name: compare
values.comment: compare two Dates.

values.name: date
values.comment:
date constructs a Date value given a year, a month and a day.
Invalid values are clamped to the nearest valid date.

values.name: day
values.comment:
day returns a Date's year as an Int. Guaranteed to be valid for
the Date's (year, month) pair and in the range [1, 31].

values.name: daysInMonth
values.comment:
daysInMonth returns the number of days in a month given a specific
year, taking leap years into account.

* A regular year has 365 days and the corresponding February has 28 days.
* A leap year has 366 days and the corresponding February has 29 days.

values.name: delta
values.comment: delta returns the relative number of years, months and days between two Dates.

values.name: fromTuple
values.comment: fromTuple converts a (year, month, day) tuple into a Date value.

values.name: isLeapYear
values.comment:
isLeapYear returns True if the given year is a leap year.  The
rules for leap years are as follows:

* A year that is a multiple of 400 is a leap year.
* A year that is a multiple of 100 but not of 400 is not a leap year.
* A year that is a multiple of 4 but not of 100 is a leap year.

values.name: isValidDate
values.comment:
isValidDate returns True if the given year, month and day
represent a valid date.

values.name: month
values.comment:
month returns a Date's month as an Int. Guaranteed to be in the
range [1, 12].

values.name: setDay
values.comment:
setDay updates a Date's day.  Invalid values are clamped to the
nearest valid date.

values.name: setMonth
values.comment:
setMonth updates a Date's month.  Invalid values are clamped to the
nearest valid date.

values.name: setYear
values.comment:
setYear updates a Date's year.  Invalid values are clamped to the
nearest valid date.

values.name: toISO8601
values.comment: toISO8601 converts a Date into its string representation.

values.name: toTuple
values.comment:
toTuple converts a Date value into a (year, month, day) tuple.
This is useful if you want to use Dates as Dict keys.

values.name: weekday
values.comment:
weekday returns the day of week for a given Date.

This uses Sakamoto's method to determine the day of week.

values.name: year
values.comment: year returns a Date's year as an Int.

docs.name: Json.Decode.Pipeline

values.name: custom
values.comment:
Run the given decoder and feed its result into the pipeline at this point.

Consider this example.

    import Json.Decode exposing (int, string, at, Decoder)
    import Decode.Pipeline exposing (decode, required, custom)


    type alias User =
      { id : Int
      , name : String
      , email : String
      }


    userDecoder : Decoder User
    userDecoder =
      decode User
        |> required "id" int
        |> custom (at [ "profile", "name" ] string)
        |> required "email" string


    result : Result String User
    result =
      Decode.decodeString
        userDecoder
        """
          {
            "id": 123,
            "email": "sam@example.com",
            "profile": {"name": "Sam"}
          }
        """
    -- Ok { id = 123, name = "Sam", email = "sam@example.com" }
values.type: Json.Decode.Decoder a -> Json.Decode.Decoder (a -> b) -> Json.Decode.Decoder b

values.name: decode
values.comment:
Begin a decoding pipeline. This is a synonym for [Json.Decode.succeed](http://package.elm-lang.org/packages/elm-lang/core/latest/Json-Decode#succeed),
intended to make things read more clearly.

    import Json.Decode exposing (int, string, float, Decoder)
    import Json.Decode.Pipeline exposing (decode, required, optional)


    type alias User =
      { id : Int
      , email : String
      , name : String
      }


    userDecoder : Decoder User
    userDecoder =
      decode User
        |> required "id" int
        |> required "email" string
        |> optional "name" string ""

values.name: hardcoded
values.comment:
Rather than decoding anything, use a fixed value for the next step in the
pipeline. `harcoded` does not look at the JSON at all.

    import Json.Decode exposing (int, string, Decoder)
    import Decode.Pipeline exposing (decode, required)


    type alias User =
      { id : Int
      , email : String
      , followers : Int
      }


    userDecoder : Decoder User
    userDecoder =
      decode User
        |> required "id" int
        |> required "email" string
        |> hardcoded 0


    result : Result String User
    result =
      Decode.decodeString
        userDecoder
        """
          {"id": 123, "email": "sam@example.com"}
        """
    -- Ok { id = 123, email = "sam@example.com", followers = 0 }

values.name: optional
values.comment:
Decode a field that may be missing or have a null value. If the field is
missing, then it decodes as the `fallback` value. If the field is present,
then `valDecoder` is used to decode its value. If `valDecoder` fails on a
`null` value, then the `fallback` is used as if the field were missing
entirely.

    import Json.Decode exposing (int, string, null, oneOf, Decoder)
    import Decode.Pipeline exposing (decode, required, optional)


    type alias User =
      { id : Int
      , name : String
      , email : String
      }


    userDecoder : Decoder User
    userDecoder =
      decode User
        |> required "id" int
        |> optional "name" string "blah"
        |> required "email" string


    result : Result String User
    result =
      Decode.decodeString
        userDecoder
        """
          {"id": 123, "email": "sam@example.com" }
        """
    -- Ok { id = 123, name = "blah", email = "sam@example.com" }

Because `valDecoder` is given an opportunity to decode `null` values before
resorting to the `fallback`, you can distinguish between missing and `null`
values if you need to:

    userDecoder2 =
        decode User
            |> required "id" int
            |> optional "name" (oneOf [ string, null "NULL" ]) "MISSING"
            |> required "email" string
values.type: String -> Json.Decode.Decoder a -> a -> Json.Decode.Decoder (a -> b) -> Json.Decode.Decoder b

values.name: optionalAt
values.comment: Decode an optional nested field.
values.type: List String -> Json.Decode.Decoder a -> a -> Json.Decode.Decoder (a -> b) -> Json.Decode.Decoder b

values.name: required
values.comment:
Decode a required field.

    import Json.Decode exposing (int, string, Decoder)
    import Decode.Pipeline exposing (decode, required)


    type alias User =
      { id : Int
      , name : String
      , email : String
      }


    userDecoder : Decoder User
    userDecoder =
      decode User
        |> required "id" int
        |> required "name" string
        |> required "email" string


    result : Result String User
    result =
      Decode.decodeString
        userDecoder
        """
          {"id": 123, "email": "sam@example.com", "name": "Sam"}
        """
    -- Ok { id = 123, name = "Sam", email = "sam@example.com" }
values.type: String -> Json.Decode.Decoder a -> Json.Decode.Decoder (a -> b) -> Json.Decode.Decoder b

values.name: requiredAt
values.comment: Decode a required nested field.
values.type: List String -> Json.Decode.Decoder a -> Json.Decode.Decoder (a -> b) -> Json.Decode.Decoder b

values.name: resolve
values.comment:
Convert a `Decoder (Result x a)` into a `Decoder a`. Useful when you want
to perform some custom processing just before completing the decoding operation.

    import Json.Decode exposing (int, string, float, Decoder)
    import Decode.Pipeline exposing
      (decode, required, resolve)


    type alias User =
      { id : Int
      , email : String
      }


    userDecoder : Decoder User
    userDecoder =
      let
        -- toDecoder gets run *after* all the
        -- (|> required ...) steps are done.
        toDecoder : Int -> String -> Int -> Decoder User
        toDecoder id email version =
          if version > 2 then
            succeed (User id email)
          else
            fail "This JSON is from a deprecated source. Please upgrade!"
      in
        decode toDecoder
          |> required "id" int
          |> required "email" string
          |> required "version" int -- version is part of toDecoder,
          |> resolve                -- but it is not a part of User


    result : Result String User
    result =
      Decode.decodeString
        userDecoder
        """
          {"id": 123, "email": "sam@example.com", "version": 1}
        """
    -- Err "This JSON is from a deprecated source. Please upgrade!"

docs.name: Array.Hamt

aliases.name: Array
aliases.comment:
Representation of fast immutable arrays. You can create arrays of integers
(`Array Int`) or strings (`Array String`) or any other type of value you can
dream up.
aliases.type: { length : Int , startShift : Int , tree : Array.Hamt.Tree a , tail : Array.JsArray.JsArray a }

values.name: append
values.comment:
Append one array onto another one.

    append (repeat 2 42) (repeat 3 81) == fromList [42,42,81,81,81]
values.type: Array.Hamt.Array a -> Array.Hamt.Array a -> Array.Hamt.Array a

values.name: empty
values.comment:
Return an empty array.

    length empty == 0

values.name: filter
values.comment:
Keep only elements that satisfy the predicate.

    filter isEven (fromList [1..6]) == (fromList [2,4,6])

values.name: foldl
values.comment:
Reduce an array from the left. Read `foldl` as fold from the left.

    foldl (::) [] (fromList [1,2,3]) == [3,2,1]
values.type: (a -> b -> b) -> b -> Array.Hamt.Array a -> b

values.name: foldr
values.comment:
Reduce an array from the right. Read `foldr` as fold from the right.

    foldr (+) 0 (repeat 3 5) == 15
values.type: (a -> b -> b) -> b -> Array.Hamt.Array a -> b

values.name: fromList
values.comment: Create an array from a list.

values.name: get
values.comment:
Return Just the element at the index or Nothing if the index is out of range.

    get  0 (fromList [0,1,2]) == Just 0
    get  2 (fromList [0,1,2]) == Just 2
    get  5 (fromList [0,1,2]) == Nothing
    get -1 (fromList [0,1,2]) == Nothing

values.name: indexedMap
values.comment:
Apply a function on every element with its index as first argument.

    indexedMap (*) (fromList [5,5,5]) == fromList [0,5,10]
values.type: (Int -> a -> b) -> Array.Hamt.Array a -> Array.Hamt.Array b

values.name: initialize
values.comment:
Initialize an array. `initialize n f` creates an array of length `n` with
the element at index `i` initialized to the result of `(f i)`.

    initialize 4 identity    == fromList [0,1,2,3]
    initialize 4 (\n -> n*n) == fromList [0,1,4,9]
    initialize 4 (always 0)  == fromList [0,0,0,0]

values.name: isEmpty
values.comment:
Determine if an array is empty.

    isEmpty empty == True

values.name: length
values.comment:
Return the length of an array.

    length (fromList [1,2,3]) == 3

values.name: map
values.comment:
Apply a function on every element in an array.

    map sqrt (fromList [1,4,9]) == fromList [1,2,3]

values.name: push
values.comment:
Push an element onto the end of an array.

    push 3 (fromList [1,2]) == fromList [1,2,3]

values.name: repeat
values.comment:
Creates an array with a given length, filled with a default element.

    repeat 5 0     == fromList [0,0,0,0,0]
    repeat 3 "cat" == fromList ["cat","cat","cat"]

Notice that `repeat 3 x` is the same as `initialize 3 (always x)`.

values.name: set
values.comment:
Set the element at a particular index. Returns an updated array.
If the index is out of range, the array is unaltered.

    set 1 7 (fromList [1,2,3]) == fromList [1,7,3]
values.type: Int -> a -> Array.Hamt.Array a -> Array.Hamt.Array a

values.name: slice
values.comment:
Get a sub-section of an array: `(slice start end array)`. The `start` is a
zero-based index where we will start our slice. The `end` is a zero-based index
that indicates the end of the slice. The slice extracts up to but not including
`end`.

    slice  0  3 (fromList [0,1,2,3,4]) == fromList [0,1,2]
    slice  1  4 (fromList [0,1,2,3,4]) == fromList [1,2,3]

Both the `start` and `end` indexes can be negative, indicating an offset from
the end of the array.

    slice  1 -1 (fromList [0,1,2,3,4]) == fromList [1,2,3]
    slice -2  5 (fromList [0,1,2,3,4]) == fromList [3,4]

This makes it pretty easy to `pop` the last element off of an array: `slice 0 -1 array`
values.type: Int -> Int -> Array.Hamt.Array a -> Array.Hamt.Array a

values.name: toIndexedList
values.comment:
Create an indexed list from an array. Each element of the array will be
paired with its index.

    toIndexedList (fromList ["cat","dog"]) == [(0,"cat"), (1,"dog")]

values.name: toList
values.comment:
Create a list of elements from an array.

    toList (fromList [3,5,8]) == [3,5,8]

docs.name: FNV
docs.comment:
FNV hash function for hashing strings

@docs hashString

values.name: hashString
values.comment:
Takes a string. Produces a hash (integer).

    hashString "Turn me into a hash" == 4138100590

docs.name: Fifo

types.name: Fifo
types.comment: A FIFO containing items of type `a`.

values.name: empty
values.comment:
Creates an empty Fifo.

    Fifo.empty
        -- == Fifo.fromList []

values.name: fromList
values.comment:
Creates a Fifo from a List.

    Fifo.fromList [3,4,5]
    |> Fifo.remove
    |> fst
        -- == Just 3

values.name: insert
values.comment:
Inserts an item into a Fifo

    Fifo.empty
    |> Fifo.insert 7
    |> Fifo.insert 8
        -- == Fifo.fromList [7,8]

values.name: remove
values.comment:
Removes the next (oldest) item from a Fifo, returning the item (if any), and the updated Fifo.

    Fifo.fromList [3,7]
    |> Fifo.remove
        -- == (Just 3, Fifo.fromList [7])
values.type: Fifo.Fifo a -> ( Maybe.Maybe a, Fifo.Fifo a )

values.name: toList
values.comment:
Converts a Fifo to a List.

    Fifo.empty
    |> Fifo.insert 7
    |> Fifo.insert 9
    |> Fifo.toList
        -- == [7,9]

docs.name: Transducer.Debug

values.name: debug
values.comment:
Wrap an existing transducer such that input and output of the transducer
will be logged with `Debug.log`.

    filter' pred = debug "filter" (filter pred)
    main = show (transduceList (filter' ((/=) 2)) [1, 2, 3])
    -- Console output:
    --     filter: input: 3
    --     filter: state: ()
    --     filter -> : 3
    --     filter: input: 2
    --     filter: state: ()
    --     filter: input: 1
    --     filter: state: ()
    --     filter -> : 1
    --     filter: complete: ()
values.type: String -> Transducer.Transducer a b r s -> Transducer.Transducer a b r s

docs.name: Transducer
docs.comment:
A transducer is a composable way of processing a series of values.
Many basic transducers correspond to functions you may be familiar with for
processing `List`s.

    import Maybe
    import String
    import Transducer exposing (..)

    parseValidInts =
        map String.toInt
        >>> map toMaybe
        >>> filter ((/=) Nothing)
        >>> map (Maybe.withDefault 0)

    exampleList : List Int
    exampleList = transduceList parseValidInts ["123", "-34", "35.0", "SDF", "7"]

# Definitions
@docs Reducer, Transducer, Fold

# Common transducers
@docs map, filter, take, drop

# More transducers
@docs concatMap, dedupe, partition

# Composing transducers
@docs (>>>), comp

# Applying transducers
@docs transduce, transduceList, transduceSet, transduceArray

aliases.name: Fold
aliases.comment:
A fold is function that takes a Reducer, an initial value, and input source,
and returns a final value.
aliases.type: Transducer.Reducer input result -> result -> source -> result

aliases.name: Reducer
aliases.comment:
A reducer is a function taking an input and a value and produces a new value.

    List.foldl : Reducer a b -> b -> List a -> b

aliases.name: Transducer
aliases.comment:
A transducer an `init` value for it's internal state, a `step` function that
transforms a Reducer into a Reducer of a new type, and a `complete` function that
transforms a Reducer into a function collapsing the internal state.

When defining transducers, the type parameter `r` should be left free.
aliases.type: { init : Transducer.Reducer b r -> r -> ( state, r ) , step : Transducer.Reducer b r -> Transducer.Reducer a ( state, r ) , complete : Transducer.Reducer b r -> ( state, r ) -> r }

values.comment: Transducer composition

aliases.name: Transformation
aliases.comment:
Representation of the 2D matrix used to transform points (x,y) in the view
plane:

    | x' |   | a  b  tx |   | x |
    | y' | = | c  d  ty | * | y |
    | 1  |   | 0  0  1  |   | 1 |
aliases.type: { a : Float , b : Float , c : Float , d : Float , tx : Float , ty : Float }

types.comment: Direction of rotation

types.name: ShearDirection
types.comment: Direction of shearing

values.name: apply
values.comment: Apply the transformation to a point.

values.name: combine
values.comment:
Combine ([compose](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transformation_matrix#Composing_and_inverting_transformations)) two transformations:

    complexShapeMovement : ( Float, Float ) -> Float -> List Point -> List Point
    complexShapeMovement offset angle points =
        let
            transform =
                combine (translate offset) (rotate Clockwise angle)
                    |> apply
        in
            List.map transform points

values.comment: Converts a point to a x,y coordinate tuple

values.name: identity
values.comment:
Creates an identity transformation for the point. This is
often used to create an initial transform that creates a local origin for a set
of points that allows them to be transformed relative to the local origin.

values.name: rotate
values.comment:
Creates a transformation that will rotate each point around the origin
by the specified direction and angle:

    rotateShape : Float -> List Point -> List Point
    rotateShape angle points =
        let
            transform =
                rotate Clockwise angle
                    |> apply
        in
            List.map transform points

values.name: scale
values.comment:
Creates a transformation that will scale each point x value by the width and
y value by the height relative to the origin:

    scaleShape : Float -> Float -> List Point -> List Point
    scaleShape width height points =
        let
            transform =
                scale width height
                    |> apply
        in
            List.map transform points

Creates a transformation that will scale each point by a factor k relative

values.name: shear

Creates a transformation that will shear each point in the given direction
by a factor of k relative to the origin

values.name: toPoint

values.name: translate
values.comment:
Creates a transformation that will move each point
by the tx ty offset amounts

docs.name: ElmTest.Extra
docs.comment:
Additions to [elm-test](http://package.elm-lang.org/packages/elm-community/elm-test/latest)
for use with the [lobo](https://www.npmjs.com/package/lobo) test runner.

    skippedTest : Test
    skippedTest =
        skip "ignore test" <|
            test "skippedTest" <|
                \() ->
                    Expect.fail "Never runs"


    focusTest : Test
    focusTest =
        focus <|
            test "Example passing test" <|
                \() ->
                    Expect.pass

## Migration from elm-test
To use this package you will need to use lobo with the "elm-test-extra"
framework, and replace:

    import Test

with

    import ElmTest.Extra

Further information on using lobo can be found [here](https://www.npmjs.com/package/lobo)

The following elm-test functions are not available in elm-test-extra:
* concat -> instead use `describe`
* filter -> instead use `skip`

## Extra

@docs focus, skip

## elm-test

lobo compatible declarations of the elm-test Test API. In the first instance
please see the original [elm-test documentation](http://package.elm-lang.org/packages/elm-community/elm-test/latest)

@docs Test, test

### Organizing Tests

@docs describe

### Fuzz Testing

@docs fuzz, fuzz2, fuzz3, fuzz4, fuzz5, fuzzWith

aliases.name: Test
aliases.comment:
A test which has yet to be evaluated.
For further help see the original [elm-test documentation](http://package.elm-lang.org/packages/elm-community/elm-test/latest)

values.name: describe
values.comment:
Group a set of tests with a description.
For further help see the original [elm-test documentation](http://package.elm-lang.org/packages/elm-community/elm-test/latest)

values.name: focus
values.comment:
Restrict the running of tests to only those that have `focus`:
unfocused tests.

    focusTest : Test
    focusTest =
        focus <|
            test "Example passing test" <|
                \() ->
                    Expect.pass

This will cause the lobo runner to ignore all other tests that don't have focus
applied. focus can be applied to the following:
* test
* describe
* fuzz, fuzzWith, fuzz2, fuzz3, fuzz4, fuzz5

Focus cannot be used to force a skipped test to run.

This will cause the lobo runner to skip this test. skip can be applied to the
following:

docs.name: BitwiseInfix
docs.comment:
This module provides infix versions of Elm's Bitwise module functions. This greatly eases conversion of existing JavaScript code. Intead of changing infix to prefix, just prepend a twiddle (~) to the operators. ```Bitwise.not``` has no infix operator, since Elm doesn't provide single argument "infix" operators. So I named it ```BitwiseInfix.lognot```, in honor of its Common Lisp name. It is intended to be imported exposing (..), so that the operators can appear unadorned in your code. All the operators are left associative. I mirrored the JavaScript precedences, putting the shift operators at lower precedence than arithmetic, but higher than comparison, and the others lower than comparison. ```(~<<)```, ```(~>>)```, and ```(~>>>)``` have a precedence of 5.
```(~&)``` has a precedence of 3.
```(~^)``` has a precedence of 2.
```(~|)``` has a precedence of 1. Examples: ``` import BitwiseInfix exposing (..) 3 ~& 1 ~| 4 ~& 12 -- 5 3 ~& (1 ~| 4) ~& 12 -- 0 2 ~<< 1 ~| 2 -- 6 2 ~<< (1 ~| 2) -- 16 1 ~| 2 ~^ 2 ~| 1 -- 1 (1 ~| 2) ~^ (2 ~| 1) -- 0 3 ~& 1 ~^ 4 ~& 12 -- 5 3 ~& (1 ~^ 4) ~& 12 -- 0 9 ~>> 1 ~<< 1 -- 8 9 ~>> (1 ~<< 1) -- 2 ``` # Functions @docs (~&), (~|), (~^), lognot, (~<<), (~>>), (~>>>)

values.name: lognot
values.comment:
Alias for Bitwise.not.
Elm does not provide "infix" operators with only a single argument.
This name let's you import BitwiseInfix exposing (..), without
worrying about name collisions.
Infix for Bitwise.and
Infix for Bitwise.shiftLeftBy
Infix for Bitwise.shiftRightBy
Infix for Bitwise.shiftRightLogical
Infix for Bitwise.xor
Infix for Bitwise.or

docs.name: DynamoBackend
docs.comment:
This module provides an Elm backend to Amazon's DynamoDB.

By itself, in pure Elm, you can only access a simulation of the Dynamo
database, with key/value pairs that persist only for the current
session. The README for the GitHub archive tells how to hook up the
JavaScript via ports to your application, and how to configure
DynamoDB via Amazon's Web Services console for use with
`DynamoBackend`.

There is a simple example that clearly illustrates the difference
between the pure-Elm simulator and the real Amazon backend.

`DynamoBackend` targets a single DynamoDB table with three
attributes. It enables use of that table by multiple Amazon accounts,
with each account's data insulated from the others. It also allows
multiple different applications to store their data in that one
backend table, without interference.

The data store is a simple key/value store, mapping a string key to
string data. I expect that one common use will be to JSON encode
state, and store it by key. I built it to do that for my application.

The one drawback of Amazon's authentication mechanism that I was not
able to work around is that a login session lasts only one hour. Each
hour, your users will have to click on the "OK" button in the login
dialog, to renew the session. I consider this to be a bug on Amazon's
part.

# Classes
@docs Profile, Properties, StringDict, DynamoServerInfo, ResultDispatcher
@docs Database, SimDb, DynamoDb
@docs ErrorType, Error

# Functions
@docs formatError, getProp, setProp, removeProp, removeProps, mergeProps
@docs makeDynamoDb, makeSimulatedDb, isRealDatabase, makeMsgCmd
@docs installLoginScript, login, retry, put, remove, get, scan, logout
@docs partialLogout, update

aliases.name: DynamoDb
aliases.comment:
Properties for a real `Dynamo` backend `Database`.

`serverInfo` - The ServerInfo record sent in as the startup "flags" from
the JavaScript.

`getProperties` - Your Model must contain a `Properties` list that the
`DynamoBackend` code can use to store state. This function extracts that
list from your `Model`.

`setProperties` - Set the `Properties` list in your `Model`.

`backendPort` - your outgoing backend `port` to the JavaScript code.

`backendMsg` - Create a message as if it came from the incoming backend
port to the JavaScript code.

`dispatcher` - The record of functions to call for return data from the
backend JavaScript.
aliases.type: { serverInfo : DynamoBackend.DynamoServerInfo , getProperties : model -> DynamoBackend.Properties , setProperties : DynamoBackend.Properties -> model -> model , backendPort : DynamoBackend.Properties -> Platform.Cmd.Cmd msg , backendMsg : DynamoBackend.Properties -> msg , dispatcher : DynamoBackend.ResultDispatcher model msg }

aliases.name: DynamoServerInfo
aliases.comment:
This record is sent to Elm as the "flags" argument from the
startup code. It is stored internally by the JavaScript backend code,
and isn't used by any of the Elm code, except that you store it in
your Dynamo database. Can be useful for debugging (though I'm tempted
to leave it solely in the JavaScript code).

The properties are setup in Amazon's AWS Console for DynamoDB, and are
stored in a JavaScript file that you create.

This is not secret information. It simply identifies your application
and the table you use to store your key/value pairs.
aliases.type: { clientId : String , tableName : String , appName : String , roleArn : String , providerId : String , awsRegion : String }

aliases.name: Error
aliases.comment: DynamoBackend.update returns errors in an `Error` record.

aliases.name: Profile
aliases.comment: The application-level result of a successful login
aliases.type: { email : String, name : String, userId : String }

aliases.name: Properties
aliases.comment:
The communication through the ports to the backend JavaScript
happens with `Properties` lists, lists of string pairs.

aliases.name: ResultDispatcher
aliases.comment:
When results return from the backend, they are passed to one of
these functions that you provide.

`DynamoBackend.login` gives results to the `ResultDispatcher.login`
function.

`DynamoBackend.get` gives results to the `ResultDispatcher.get`
function.

`DynamoBackend.put` and `DynamoBackend.remove` give results to the
`ResultDispatcher.put` function.

`DynamoBackend.scan` gives results to the `ResultDispatcher.scan`
function.

`DynamoBackend.logout` results to the `ResultDispatcher.logout`
function.
aliases.type: { login : DynamoBackend.Profile -> DynamoBackend.Database model msg -> model -> ( model, Platform.Cmd.Cmd msg ) , get : String -> Maybe.Maybe String -> DynamoBackend.Database model msg -> model -> ( model, Platform.Cmd.Cmd msg ) , put : String -> Maybe.Maybe String -> DynamoBackend.Database model msg -> model -> ( model, Platform.Cmd.Cmd msg ) , scan : List String -> List String -> DynamoBackend.Database model msg -> model -> ( model, Platform.Cmd.Cmd msg ) , logout : DynamoBackend.Database model msg -> model -> ( model, Platform.Cmd.Cmd msg ) }

aliases.name: SimDb
aliases.comment:
Properties for a simulated backend `Database`.

`profile` - A fake login `Profile`.

`getDict` - Return from your `Model` an Elm `Dict` in which the
simulator can store its key/value pairs.

`setDict` - Set the dictionary in your `Model`.

`simulatedPort` - This simulates the return port from the real
backend. `DynamoBackend.makeMsgCmd` is often useful for turning one of
your messages into a `Cmd`.

`dispatcher` - The `ResultDispatcher` that will handle the values returned
through the `simulatedPort`.
aliases.type: { profile : DynamoBackend.Profile , getDict : model -> DynamoBackend.StringDict , setDict : DynamoBackend.StringDict -> model -> model , simulatedPort : DynamoBackend.Properties -> Platform.Cmd.Cmd msg , dispatcher : DynamoBackend.ResultDispatcher model msg }

aliases.name: StringDict
aliases.comment:
An Elm `Dict` mapping `String` keys to `String` values.

You need to provide one of these in your Model for the simulated
backend.

types.name: Database
types.comment: The generic type for a `Simulated` or `Dynamo` database

types.name: ErrorType
types.comment:
Errors that can be returned in the errorType property of an Error
record.

`AccessExpired` - Happens when your Amazon login session expires. Your
application needs to call `DynamoBackend.login` again to establish a new
session.

`FetchProfileError` - denotes a problem in turning an access token into a
profile.

`AccessTokenError` - Either Amazon didn't return the state arg when
logging in, or a cross-site forgery made the state sent not match the
state received.

`InternalError` - denotes a bug in the `DynamoBackend` code. Shouldn't
happen.

`ReturnedProfileError` - Means that Amazon's return for profile lookup
was missing the email, name, or userId.

`AwsError` - An error was returned by the Amazon AWS JavaScript
library. Usually denotes a network problem.

`Other` - Shouldn't happen. Means that that the backend code neglected
to tag an error with an "errorType".

docs.name: Return

aliases.name: ReturnF
aliases.type: Return.Return msg model -> Return.Return msg model

values.comment:
Go point free with `andThen` chaining. Looking at the example from `andThen`

```elm
resulting : Return msg { model | bar : Int }
resulting = myReturn
    |> andThen foo
    |> andThen foo
    |> andThen foo
```

this code roughly becomes:

```elm
doFoo3Times : { model | bar : Int } -> Return msg { model | bar : Int }
doFoo3Times =
  foo >>> foo >>> foo
```
values.type: (b -> Return.Return msg c) -> (a -> Return.Return msg b) -> a -> Return.Return msg c
(a -> Return.Return msg b) -> (b -> Return.Return msg c) -> a -> Return.Return msg c

values.name: andMap
values.comment: Map an `Return` into a `Return` containing a `Model` function
values.type: Return.Return msg (a -> b) -> Return.Return msg a -> Return.Return msg b

values.name: andThen
values.comment:
Chain together expressions from `Model` to `Return`.

```elm
-- arbitrary function to demonstrate
foo : Model -> Return Msg Model
foo ({bar} as model) =
  -- forking logic
  if bar < 10
  -- that side effects may be added
  then (model, getAjaxThing)
  -- that the model may be updated
  else ({model | bar = model.bar - 2 }, Cmd.none)
```

They are now chainable with `andThen`...

```elm
resulting : Return msg { model | bar : Int }
resulting = myReturn
    |> andThen foo
    |> andThen foo
    |> andThen foo
```

Here we changed up `foo` three times, but we can use any function of
type `(a -> Return msg b)`.

Commands will be accumulated automatically as is the case with all
functions in this library.
values.type: (a -> Return.Return msg b) -> Return.Return msg a -> Return.Return msg b

values.name: command
values.comment: Add a `Cmd` to a `Return`, the `Model` is uneffected

values.name: dropCmd
values.comment: Drop the current `Cmd` and replace with an empty thunk

values.name: effect_
values.comment: Add a `Cmd` to a `Return` based on its `Model`, the `Model` will not be effected
values.type: Respond.Respond msg model -> Return.ReturnF msg model

values.name: flatten
values.type: Return.Return msg (Return.Return msg model) -> Return.Return msg model

values.name: map
values.comment: Transform the `Model` the `Cmd` will be left untouched
values.type: (a -> b) -> Return.Return msg a -> Return.Return msg b

values.name: map2
values.comment:
Combine 2 `Return`s with a function

```elm
map2
  (\modelA modelB -> { modelA | foo = modelB.foo })
  retA
  retB
```
values.type: (a -> b -> c) -> Return.Return msg a -> Return.Return msg b -> Return.Return msg c

values.name: mapBoth
values.comment:
Map over both the model and the msg type of the `Return`.
This is useful for easily embedding a `Return` in a Union Type.
For example

```elm
import Foo

type Msg = Foo Foo.Msg
type Model = FooModel Foo.Model

...

update : Msg -> Model -> Return Msg Model
update msg model =
   case msg of
     Foo foo -> Foo.update foo model.foo
      |> mapBoth Foo FooModel
```

docs.name: RemoteData

aliases.name: WebData
aliases.comment:
While `RemoteData` can model any type of error, the most common
one you'll actually encounter is when you fetch data from a REST
interface, and get back `RemoteData Http.Error a`. Because that case
is so common, `WebData` is provided as a useful alias.

types.name: RemoteData
types.comment:
Frequently when you're fetching data from an API, you want to represent four different states:
  * `NotAsked` - We haven't asked for the data yet.
  * `Loading` - We've asked, but haven't got an answer yet.
  * `Failure` - We asked, but something went wrong. Here's the error.
  * `Success` - Everything worked, and here's the data.

values.type: (a -> b) -> RemoteData.RemoteData e a -> RemoteData.RemoteData e b
RemoteData.RemoteData e (a -> b) -> RemoteData.RemoteData e a -> RemoteData.RemoteData e b

values.name: andThen
values.comment: Chain together RemoteData function calls.
values.type: RemoteData.RemoteData e a -> (a -> RemoteData.RemoteData e b) -> RemoteData.RemoteData e b

values.name: append
values.comment:
Append - join two `RemoteData` values together as though
they were one.

If either value is `NotAsked`, the result is `NotAsked`.
If either value is `Loading`, the result is `Loading`.
If both values are `Failure`, the left one wins.
values.type: RemoteData.RemoteData e a -> RemoteData.RemoteData e b -> RemoteData.RemoteData e ( a, b )

values.name: apply
values.comment:
Applicative instance for `RemoteData`.

If you know what that means, then you know if you need this.

If not, this probably isn't the place for an applicatve tutorial, but
the gist is it makes it easy to create functions that merge several
`RemoteData` values together. For example, `RemoteData.append` is
implemented as:

    append a b =
        (,) <$> a <*> b
values.type: RemoteData.RemoteData e (a -> b) -> RemoteData.RemoteData e a -> RemoteData.RemoteData e b

values.name: asCmd
values.comment: Convert a web `Task`, probably produced from elm-http, to a `Cmd (RemoteData e a)`.
values.type: Task.Task e a -> Platform.Cmd.Cmd (RemoteData.RemoteData e a)

values.name: fromResult
values.comment: Convert a `Result Error`, probably produced from elm-http, to a RemoteData value.
values.type: Result.Result e a -> RemoteData.RemoteData e a

values.name: fromTask
values.comment:
Convert from a `Task` that may succeed or fail, to one that always
succeeds with the `RemoteData` that captures any errors.
values.type: Task.Task e a -> Task.Task Basics.Never (RemoteData.RemoteData e a)

values.name: isFailure
values.comment: State-checking predicate. Returns true if we've failed to load some data.

values.name: isLoading
values.comment: State-checking predicate. Returns true if we're loading.

values.name: isNotAsked
values.comment: State-checking predicate. Returns true if we haven't asked for data yet.

values.name: isSuccess
values.comment: State-checking predicate. Returns true if we've successfully loaded some data.

values.name: map
values.comment: Map a function into the `Success` value.
values.type: (a -> b) -> RemoteData.RemoteData e a -> RemoteData.RemoteData e b

values.name: mapBoth
values.comment: Map function into both the `Success` and `Failure` value.
values.type: (a -> b) -> (e -> f) -> RemoteData.RemoteData e a -> RemoteData.RemoteData f b

values.name: mapFailure
values.comment: Map a function into the `Failure` value.
values.type: (e -> f) -> RemoteData.RemoteData e a -> RemoteData.RemoteData f a

values.name: prism
values.comment:
A monocle-compatible Prism.

If you use Monocle, you'll want this, otherwise you can ignore it.

The type signature is actually:

``` elm
prism : Prism (RemoteData e a) a
```

...but we use the more verbose type here to avoid introducing a dependency on Monocle.
values.type: { getOption : RemoteData.RemoteData e a -> Maybe.Maybe a , reverseGet : a -> RemoteData.RemoteData e a }

values.name: toMaybe
values.comment: Convert a `RemoteData e a` to a `Maybe a`

values.name: update
values.comment:
Apply an Elm update function - `Model -> (Model, Cmd Msg)` - to any `Successful`-ly loaded data.

It's quite common in Elm to want to run a model-update function, over
some remote data, but only once it's actually been loaded.

For example, we might want to handle UI messages changing the users
settings, but that only makes sense once those settings have been
returned from the server.

This function makes it more convenient to reach inside a
`RemoteData.Success` value and apply an update. If the data is not
`Success a`, it is returned unchanged with a `Cmd.none`.
values.type: (a -> ( b, Platform.Cmd.Cmd c )) -> RemoteData.RemoteData e a -> ( RemoteData.RemoteData e b, Platform.Cmd.Cmd c )

values.name: withDefault
values.comment: Return the `Success` value, or the default.

UnitType

Represents an absolute or relative unit of length. A length of zero may be
