docs.name: Either

values.name: andMap
values.comment:
Apply the function that is inside `Either` to a value that is inside
`Either`. Return the result inside `Either`. If one of the `Either`
arguments is `Left x`, return `Left x`. Also known as `apply`.

    Left "Hello" |> andMap (Left "World")  == Left "Hello"
    Left "Hello" |> andMap (Right 2)       == Left "Hello"
    Right ((+) 1) |> andMap (Left "World") == Left "World"
    Right ((+) 1) |> andMap (Right 2)      == Right 3
values.type: Either.Either x a -> Either.Either x (a -> b) -> Either.Either x b

values.name: andMapLeft
values.comment:
Apply the function that is inside `Either` to a value that is inside
`Either`. Return the result inside `Either`. If one of the `Either`
arguments is `Right x`, return `Right x`. Also known as `apply`.

    Left (flip (++) "!!" ) |> andMap Left "Hello" == Left "Hello!!"
    Left (flip (++) "!!" ) |> andMap Right 2      == Right 2
    Right 99 |> andMap (Left "World")             == Right 99
    Right 99 |> andMap (Right 2)                  == Right 99
values.type: Either.Either a x -> Either.Either (a -> b) x -> Either.Either b x

values.name: andMapRight
values.comment: Alias for `andMap`.
values.type: Either.Either x a -> Either.Either x (a -> b) -> Either.Either x b

values.name: andThen
values.comment:
Chain together in many computations that will stop computing if
a chain is on a `Left`. Also known as `bind`.

    Left "Hello" |> andThen ((+) 1 >> Right) == Left "Hello"
    Right 2 |> andThen ((+) 1 >> Right)      == Right 3
values.type: (a -> Either.Either x b) -> Either.Either x a -> Either.Either x b

values.name: andThenLeft
values.comment:
Chain together in many computations that will stop computing if
a chain is on a `Right`. Also known as `bind`.

    Left "Hello" |> andThen (flip (++) "!!" >> Left) == Left "Hello!!"
    Right 2 |> andThen (flip (++) "!!" >> Left)      == Right 2
values.type: (a -> Either.Either b x) -> Either.Either a x -> Either.Either b x

values.name: andThenRight
values.comment: Alias for `andThen`.
values.type: (a -> Either.Either x b) -> Either.Either x a -> Either.Either x b

values.name: foldr
values.comment:
Folds an `Either` over a function with an accumulator. If
it is a `Right` the function is applied with the accumulator.
If it is a `Left` only the accumulator is returned.

    foldr (*) 2 <| Left 3  == 2
    foldr (*) 2 <| Right 3 == 6
values.type: (a -> b -> b) -> b -> Either.Either a a -> b

values.name: fromLeft
values.comment:
Extract left value or a default.

    fromLeft "World" <| Left "Hello" == "Hello"
    fromLeft "World" <| Right 2      == "World"

values.name: fromMaybe
values.comment:
Convert from a `Maybe` to `Either` with a default value
for `Left` for `Nothing`.

    fromMaybe "Hello" <| Just 2 == Right 2
    fromMaybe "Hello" Nothing   == Left "Hello"
values.type: a -> Maybe.Maybe b -> Either.Either a b

values.name: fromResult
values.comment:
Convert from `Result` to `Either`.

    fromResult <| Err "World" == Left "World"
    fromResult <| Ok 2        == Right 2
values.type: Result.Result a b -> Either.Either a b

values.name: fromRight
values.comment:
Extract right value or a default.

    fromRight 3 <| Left "Hello" == 3
    fromRight 3 <| Right 2      == 2

values.name: isLeft
values.comment:
Returns `True` if argument is `Left _`

    isLeft <| Left "World" == True
    isLeft <| Right 2      == False

values.name: isRight
values.comment:
Returns `True` if argument is `Right _`

    isRight <| Left "World" == False
    isRight <| Right 2      == True

values.name: leftFromMaybe
values.comment:
Convert from a `Maybe` to `Either` with a default value
for `Right` for `Nothing`.

    leftFromMaybe 3 <| Just "World" == Left "World"
    leftFromMaybe 3 Nothing         == Right 3
values.type: b -> Maybe.Maybe a -> Either.Either a b

values.name: leftToMaybe
values.comment:
`Maybe` get the `Left` side of an `Either`.

    leftToMaybe <| Left "World" == Just "World"
    leftToMaybe <| Right 2 == Nothing

values.name: lefts
values.comment:
Converts a `List` of `Either a x` to a List of `a`.

    lefts [ Left "Hello", Right 2 ] == [ "Hello" ]

values.name: length
values.comment:
Returns the length of an `Either`. This happens to be `0` for a
`Left` and `1` for a `Right`.

    length <| Left 2         == 0
    length <| Right "Sharks" == 1

values.name: map
values.comment:
Apply a function to an `Either`. If the argument is `Right`, it
will be converted.  If the argument is an `Left`, the same left value
will propogate through.

    map ((+) 1) <| Left "Hello" == Left "Hello"
    map ((+) 1) <| Right 2      == Right 3
values.type: (a -> b) -> Either.Either x a -> Either.Either x b

values.name: map2
values.comment:
Apply a function to two eithers, if both arguments are `Right`.
If not, the first argument which is a `Left` will propagate through.
Also known as `liftA2`.

    map2 (+) (Left "Hello") <| Left "World" == Left "Hello"
    map2 (+) (Left "Hello") <| Right 3      == Left "Hello"
    map2 (+) (Right 2) <| Left "World"      == Left "World"
    map2 (+) (Right 2) <| Right 3           == Right 5
values.type: (a -> b -> c) -> Either.Either x a -> Either.Either x b -> Either.Either x c

values.name: map3
values.comment: Like `map2`, but with 3 eithers. Also known as `liftA3`
values.type: (a -> b -> c -> d) -> Either.Either x a -> Either.Either x b -> Either.Either x c -> Either.Either x d

values.name: map4
values.comment: Like `map2`, but with 4 eithers. Also known as `liftA4`
values.type: (a -> b -> c -> d -> e) -> Either.Either x a -> Either.Either x b -> Either.Either x c -> Either.Either x d -> Either.Either x e

values.name: mapBoth
values.comment:
Apply the first argument function to a `Left` and the second
argument function to a `Right` of an `Either`.

    mapBoth (flip (++) "!!") ((+) 1) <| Left "Hello" == Left "Hello!!"
    mapBoth (flip (++) "!!") ((+) 1) <| Right 2      == Right 3
values.type: (a -> b) -> (c -> d) -> Either.Either a c -> Either.Either b d

values.name: mapLeft
values.comment:
Apply a function to the `Left` of an `Either`.

    mapLeft ((+) 1) <| Left 2  == Left 3
    mapLeft ((+) 1) <| Right 2 == Right 2
values.type: (a -> b) -> Either.Either a x -> Either.Either b x

values.name: mapRight
values.comment: Alias for `map`.
values.type: (a -> b) -> Either.Either x a -> Either.Either x b

values.name: partition
values.comment:
Converts a `List` of `Either a b`, into a tuple2 where
the first value is a `List a` and the second is `List b`.

    partition [ Left "Hello", Right 2 ] == ( [ "Hello" ], [ 2 ] )
values.type: List (Either.Either a b) -> ( List a, List b )

values.name: rightFromMaybe
values.comment: Alias for `fromMaybe`.
values.type: a -> Maybe.Maybe b -> Either.Either a b

values.name: rightToMaybe
values.comment: Alias for `toMaybe`.

values.name: rights
values.comment:
Converts a `List` of `Either x b` to a List of `b`.

    rights [ Left "Hello", Right 2 ] == [ 2 ]

values.name: singleton
values.comment:
Create a `singleton` from a value to an `Either` with a `Right`
of the same type.  Also known as `pure`. Use the `Left` constructor
for a singleton of the `Left` variety.

    singleton 2 == Right 2

values.name: swap
values.comment:
Swap the `Left` and `Right` sides of an `Either`.

    swap <| Left "World" == Right "World"
    swap <| Right 2      == Left 2
values.type: Either.Either a b -> Either.Either b a

values.name: toMaybe
values.comment:
`Maybe` get the `Right` side of an `Either`.

    toMaybe <| Left "World" == Nothing
    toMaybe <| Right 2      == Just 2

values.name: toResult
values.comment:
Convert from `Either` to `Result`.

    toResult <| Left "World" == Err "World"
    toResult <| Right 2      == Ok 2
values.type: Either.Either a b -> Result.Result a b

values.name: unpack
values.comment:
Given a function for both `Left` and `Right` to to type a generic
type `c`, collapse down the `Either` to a value of that type.

    unpack identity toString <| Left "World" == "World"
    unpack identity toString <| Right 2      == "2"
values.type: (a -> c) -> (b -> c) -> Either.Either a b -> c

values.name: unwrap
values.comment:
Apply a function to `Right` value. If argument was a `Left` use the
default value. Equivalent to `Either.map >> Either.fromRight`.

    unwrap 99 ((+) 1) <| Left "Hello" == 99
    unwrap 99 ((+) 1) <| Right 2      == 3
values.type: c -> (b -> c) -> Either.Either x b -> c

values.name: withDefault
values.comment: Alias for `fromRight`.

values.name: decoder
values.comment:
JSON decoder to turn nested arrays into an Array2D.

If the rows are jagged, all rows will be truncated to the
same length as the shortest row!

docs.name: Array2D
docs.comment:
Implements 2D array using nested Arrays. Useful for implementing data grids,
as it specifically provides row and column operations.

Cells are accessed by row, then column. Otherwise, it works very similarly to the
Array class. The documentation examples usually omit converting Lists to Arrays
for brevity.

Array2D's can be constructed from an Array or List of rows, where each
row is an Array or List of cells.

    Array2D.fromList
      [ ["Row 1-Col 1", "Row 1-Col 2"]
      , ["Row 2-Col 1", "Row 2-Col 2"]
      ]

If the nested arrays happen to be jagged, all rows will be truncated to the
length of the smallest row! Be careful!

    Array2D.fromList
      [ [0, 1]
      , [0, 1, 2]
      ]
    -- Becomes:
      [ [0, 1]
      , [0, 1]
      ]


## Drawbacks and caveats

Most examples of nested Elm components use Lists of elements with a
unique, constant ID. This allows messages to always be routed to the correct
sub-component, even if components are removed or added. If you use the index
of the sub-component instead and the sub-component triggers a Task that takes
time to complete during which the Array is modified, the completion message
may be routed to the wrong sub-component.

This is hypothetical though. If your sub-components don't trigger long tasks
or you don't allow rows or columns to be manipulated until the task returns,
you should be fine. I think!


@docs Array2D

# Initialization
@docs empty, fromArray, fromList, repeat

# Getting info
@docs rows, columns, isEmpty

# Fetching/updating individual cells
@docs get, set

# Adding/removing rows
@docs getRow, appendRow, deleteRow

# Adding/removing columns
@docs getColumn, appendColumn, deleteColumn

# Mapping cell data
@docs map, indexedMap

aliases.name: Array2D
aliases.comment: Base Array2D type

values.name: appendColumn
values.comment:
Append a column. Filler will be used if the column length
is less than the number of rows in the Array2D. If it is longer,
it will be truncated.

    appendColumn [2, 2] [[1], [1]] == [[1, 2], [1,2]]
values.type: Array.Array a -> a -> Array2D.Array2D a -> Array2D.Array2D a

values.name: appendRow
values.comment:
Append a row. If the row is too long, it will be truncated,
too short and it will be expanded with filler elements.

    appendRow [3, 4] [[1, 2]] == [[1, 2], [3, 4]]
values.type: Array.Array a -> a -> Array2D.Array2D a -> Array2D.Array2D a

values.name: columns
values.comment:
Get the number of columns in an Array2D

    columns [[1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]] == 3

values.name: deleteColumn
values.comment: Delete a column. If the index is invalid, nothing will happen.

values.name: deleteRow
values.comment: Delete a row

values.name: empty
values.comment: Create an empty Array2D

values.name: fromArray
values.comment:
Create an Array2D from an Array of Arrays. All rows will
be truncated to the length of the shortest row.

    let
      row1 = Array.fromList [1, 2]
      row2 = Array.fromList [2, 3]
    in
      fromArray (Array.fromList [row1, row2])

values.name: fromList
values.comment:
Create an Array2D from a List of Lists.

    fromList [[1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]]

values.name: get
values.comment:
Get a cell.

    get 1 1 [[1, 2], [3, 4]] == Just 4
values.type: Int -> Int -> Array2D.Array2D a -> Maybe.Maybe a

values.name: getColumn
values.comment:
get column-th cell of each row as an Array

    getColumn 1 [[1, 2], [3, 4]] == [Just 2, Just 4]

values.name: getRow
values.comment:
Get an individual row

    getRow 1 [[1, 2], [3, 4]] == Just [3, 4]

values.name: indexedMap
values.comment:
2D version of Array.indexedMap. First two arguments of map function are the row and column.

    indexedMap (\row column cell -> toString row) [[1, 2], [3, 4]] == [["0", "0"], ["1", "1"]]
values.type: (Int -> Int -> a -> b) -> Array2D.Array2D a -> Array2D.Array2D b

values.name: isEmpty
values.comment:
Check if an Array2D is empty.

    isEmpty [] == True

values.name: map
values.comment:
2D version of Array.map.

    map (\cell -> toString cell) [[1, 2], [3, 4]] == [["1", "2"], ["3", "4"]]

values.name: repeat
values.comment:
Create a 2D of a given size, filled with a default element.
Similar to Array.repeat

    repeat 2 3 0 == [[0, 0, 0], [0, 0, 0]]

values.name: rows
values.comment:
Get the number of rows in an Array2D

    rows [[1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]] == 2

values.name: set
values.comment:
Update a cell, returning the changed Array2D.

    set 0 0 -100 [[1, 2], [3, 4]] == [[-100, 2], [3, 4]]
values.type: Int -> Int -> a -> Array2D.Array2D a -> Array2D.Array2D a
